  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he brake in pieces the images",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "pillars",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the comment on 1 Kings 14:23) - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and out down the groves",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "asherirn",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or \"sacred trees\" - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and filled their places with the bones of men.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Whatever spoke of death and dissolution was a special defilement to shrines where the gods worshipped were deities of productivity and generation. Bones of men had also the actual taint of corruption about them. The \"uncleanness\" of dead bodies arose first out of man's natural shrinking from death, and was then further confirmed by the horrors accompanying decay. The notion was probably coeval with death itself. It received a sanction from the Law, which made it a legal defilement to touch a corpse (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 19:11, 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and placed under a sentence of uncleanness all that was in the tent where a man died (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 19:14, 15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). 2 Kings 23:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The places of sacrifice built by Solomon upon the southern height of the Mount of Olives (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Josiah defiled, reducing to ruins the monuments, cutting down the Asherah idols, and filling their places with human bones, which polluted a place, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 19:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " gives a more precise definition of טמּא in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the form of a simple addition (with Vav cop.). הר־המּשׁחית, mountain of destruction (not unctionis  equals  המּשׁחה, Rashi and Cler.), is the southern peak of the Mount of Olives, called in the tradition of the Church mons offensionis or scandali (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). For מצּבוה and אשׁרים see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". מקומם are the places where the Mazzeboth and Asherim stood by the altars that were dedicated to Baal and Astarte, so that by defiling them the altar-places were also defiled.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]